  </section>

  <!-- Pontoon -->
  <section class="ed-section">
    <div class="ed-section-head"><h2>Renting a pontoon</h2></div>
    <div class="ed-prose">
      <p>Worth doing for at least a few days. Peer-to-peer rentals through <a class="ed-link" href="https://www.boatsetter.com" target="_blank">Boatsetter</a> are straightforward, and there are local marinas around the lake too. Book the middle of the week so you're not fighting weekend crowds.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="ed-grid">

      <div class="ed-cell">
        <div class="ttl">What to look for</div>
        <div class="body">
          <strong>Tritoon, ~150hp</strong>
          <div class="leg">
            A triple-tube pontoon around 22 ft comfortably seats a big group. Look for a Bluetooth stereo, swim ladder, anchor, and life jackets included. A 150hp tritoon pulls tubes easily; wakeboarding is doable but not aggressive.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="ed-cell">
        <div class="ttl">Add-ons to ask about</div>
        <div class="body">
          <div class="leg">
            Many rentals offer paddleboards, a floating mat or island, fishing gear, a cooler, tubes, and wakeboards. Decide up front so they're loaded before pickup.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="ed-cell">
        <div class="ttl">Good to know</div>
        <div class="body">
          <div class="leg">
            Most owner rentals are self-drive (no captain). Fuel is usually not included, so refuel before you return to avoid a service fee. Being late runs into hourly and late charges. Check the cancellation window before you book.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>

